article.description:
Camille Little collected 17 points and 10 rebounds as the top-seeded Tar
Heels pulled away from ninth-seeded Virginia, 82-56, to advance
to the semifinals of the Atlantic Coast Conference tournament.
article.headline: Little nets double-double as UNC downs UVA to advance
article.linkText: No. 1 UNC overcomes sluggish first half to down UVA
article.story:
GREENSBORO, N.C. (AP) -- One brilliant half was good enough for
No. 1 North Carolina.
	   Camille Little had 17 points and 10 rebounds, Ivory Latta added
17 points and the Tar Heels overcame a sluggish start to beat
Virginia 82-56 Friday in the quarterfinals of the Atlantic Coast
Conference tournament.
	   "A little sloppy at times, but we knew it was going to be a
tough game," UNC coach Sylvia Hatchell said. "We're a team, with
the tempo we play, lots of times we play in runs. We felt like we
eventually could go on a run and get a pretty good lead."
	   Four players scored in double figures for the Tar Heels (27-1),
who won handily despite shooting only 40 percent from the field.
But they converted 23-of-30 at the line to extend their record for
tournament victories to 42.
	   La'Tangela Atkinson added 15 points and LaToya Pringle scored 14
to reach double figures for the first time since New Year's Eve,
helping to offset an uncharacteristically poor shooting performance
from leading scorer Latta, who made only one of her first nine
shots.
	   "I noticed it and I walked over to her and told her to just
keep her head up, and just pushing the ball and keep looking for
her shot," Atkinson said of Latta's struggles.
	   At least Latta made a 3-pointer for the 56th straight game,
swishing one with about 3 minutes left for a 74-50 lead. She added
another about 60 seconds later before leaving to a rousing ovation
from the large crowd made up mostly of elementary school students
for the matinee game.
	   Latta's teammates more than took up the slack, with Pringle
giving perhaps her best effort of the season and Little
aggressively attacking the basket throughout.
	   "That's why I love these kids, they play so hard for me,"
Hatchell said. "They play hard for each other, but I'm the coach,
so I think they play hard for me, too. I'm really proud of that."
	   North Carolina wasn't challenged in the final 13 minutes and
moves on to play the winner of the Florida State-North Carolina
State game.
	   "I remember there was a point when we were running hard, and
getting some easy shots and layups," Little said. "We were
playing good defense and creating turnovers, and that helped us
out."
	   Sharnee Zoll had 13 points and Takisha Granberry scored 12 for
Virginia (18-10), which had won five in a row to move into
contention for an NCAA bid. A 5-9 ACC record in the regular season
might leave veteran coach Debbie Ryan and her team relegated to the
WNIT.
	   "I just hope and pray that my season doesn't end here, and for
it to continue on no matter where we go," forward Tiffany Sardin
said.
	   The Cavaliers were within two in the second half following a
free throw from Lyndra Littles when the Tar Heels pulled away.
Pringle powered inside for a layup to start a 21-3 run, capped by
Little's 3 off a nice feed out of the post from Erlana Larkins and
a spinning basket by Atkinson.
	   That made it 64-46.
	   "I don't know what happened to us, but the doors blew off,"
Ryan said. "Carolina exposed about everything that was wrong about
our team in that one stretch there, and that was all she wrote."
	   The Cavaliers didn't have an answer as they did in the first
half. They never led but managed to keep the margin close, holding
North Carolina to 31 percent shooting before halftime. Denesha
Kenion had all 11 of her points in that span, and Virginia trailed
only 33-29.
	   "Even though we got down a little bit, we still made a little
run to come back," Ryan said. "We played a pretty good first
half. We showed a lot of character and courage in the first half,
being able to match them point for point."
